# CI Workflow Triggers

## Build & Publish (`.github/workflows/build.yml`)

| Event | Native builds (`build-linux`, `build-host`) | Checks (`test`, publish dry-run) | Release publish |
|---|---|---|---|
| **PR → `main`** | yes | yes | dry-run only |
| **Push → `main`** | yes | no | no |
| **`release/*` tag** | yes | yes | yes |
| Push / PR on other branches | no | no | no |

Do **not** add `push` triggers for feature branches (`initial-feature`, etc.) or `pull_request` targets other than `main`. Feature-branch commits stay off CI until there is a PR to `main`.

## CI Docker image (`.github/workflows/ci-image.yml`)

Rebuild and push `ghcr.io/.../ci-build:latest` **only when**:

- The **`ci` branch** is pushed (Dockerfile or workflow changes land there)
- **`workflow_dispatch`** is triggered manually

The main build workflow always pulls `:latest`; it never rebuilds the image.

## Local validation before changing `docker/ci/`

When editing the CI Dockerfile, run locally before committing:

```bash
docker build -t node-webrtc-rust-ci-build:local docker/ci
docker run --rm node-webrtc-rust-ci-build:local sh -c 'node --version && rustc --version && zig version'
```

Then push to `ci` to publish the updated image before expecting green Linux jobs.
